Let $A,$ $B,$ $C,$ $D,$ $E,$ and $F$ be the vertices of the regular octahedron, where vertices $C,$ $D,$ and $E$ are at the endpoints of the three mutually perpendicular diameters. Thus, we can assume that:
\begin{align*}
A &= 120^\circ\text{ of radius} \\
B &= -120^\circ\text{ of radius} \\
C &= 0^\circ\text{ of radius} \\
D &= 90^\circ\text{ of radius} \\
E &= -90^\circ\text{ of radius} \\
F &= 0^\circ\text{ of radius} \\
\end{align*}> <answer>So, $P$ is a point at an angle of $105^\circ$ of radius. Applying the law of cosines to $\triangle BAP,$ we obtain:
\begin{align*}
25&=3^2+BP^2-\left(6\times3\times\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\right)BP+B+8\\
&=9+BP^2-9\sqrt{3}BP+B+8\\
BP^2-9\sqrt{3}BP+B+7&=16\\
BP^2-9\sqrt{3}BP+B-9&=0\\
\Rightarrow (BP-3\sqrt{3})(BP-3)&=0\\
\Rightarrow BP&=\boxed{3\sqrt{3}}.
\end{align*}> 
